## 5. Anti-Mock Philosophy

{% if test_environment is defined and test_environment.services is defined and test_environment.services and test_environment.services | length > 0 %}We have working infrastructure on this box:
{% for svc in test_environment.services %}- **{{ svc.name }}** @ `{{ svc.endpoint }}`{% if svc.note is defined %} ({{ svc.note }}){% endif %}
{% endfor %}

**Use them. Don't mock them.** Tests written against real services find the bugs that matter (race conditions, encoding issues, schema mismatches, payload-filter quirks).
{% else %}Wherever real services are available locally, use them rather than mocks. Tests written against real services find the bugs that matter (race conditions, encoding issues, schema mismatches, payload-filter quirks).
{% endif %}

```python
# GOOD — real service against test-suffix collection
@pytest.fixture
def real_test_collection():
    client = ServiceClient("...")
    name = f"{{ project.slug }}_test_{uuid4().hex[:8]}"
    client.create(name)
    yield client, name
    client.delete(name)

# BAD — mocked service
@pytest.fixture
def mock_service():
    return MagicMock()  # hides every service-specific bug
```

**Acceptable mocks:** external paid APIs, services we cannot run locally, network calls to hosts that may not be reachable in CI. When mocking is unavoidable, document WHY in the test file as a comment.

